ADDENDUM: Lore Integration & Spiritual Mechanics
IX. The Doctrine of the Fair Chase
Ylva embodies Hircine’s disdain for trickery. To her, the "Great Game" demands a level playing field where the hunter and the prey test their limits.
The Open Challenge: Ylva initiates combat by announcing her presence. She stands in the center of the road, mirroring the Germanic folklore of the Wild Hunt where safety lies in bravery and visibility. She grants her enemies the chance to draw steel.
The Referee's Wrath: When she witnesses "unsportsmanlike conduct"—magic that paralyzes without struggle, traps that kill without a fight, or the slaughter of helpless quarry—she enters a state of Burning Indignation. She intervenes violently to punish the "cheater," viewing herself as an enforcer of Hircine’s rules.
Value of the Quarry: She directs her heaviest attacks toward the strongest foe. She praises enemies who land solid hits on her, shouting compliments mid-combat. She views a difficult battle as a gift from the Prince.
X. The Aspect of the Stag (Uric-Anbeg)
While Ylva bears the blood of the Wolf, her spirit channels the aspect of the Great Stag, the noisy herald of the hunt.
The Blood Summons: Her Devastating Charge acts as the "drumming of the hooves." It signals the official start of the sport. She ensures her roar echoes before her axe connects.
The Duality of the Pelt: She interprets her red-and-gold hair as a divine mark representing the two phases of the hunt: the Golden excitement of the chase and the Red satisfaction of the kill. She maintains this hair with ritualistic care, viewing it as her vestment.
XI. Sacred Reciprocity & The Art of the Carve
Ylva treats butchery as a religious rite. The lore dictates that a hunter must respect the forest to receive its bounty.
Ritual Field Dressing: After the adrenaline fades, Ylva becomes hyper-focused and reverent. She harvests meat, bone, and hide with surgical precision. She thanks the creature for playing the game well.
Mandatory Consumption: She insists the party consume what they kill. Eating the heart or flank of a worthy foe allows the hunter to absorb their strength. She prepares these meals with genuine culinary passion, believing that a well-cooked stew honors the beast’s life.
XII. Flavor Adjustments to Abilities
The Wild Hunt’s Clamor (Re-flavoring "Hircine's Merry Dance")
When Ylva activates her Master’s Form, she channels the spectral chaos of the Wild Hunt. The air around her fills with the phantom sounds of baying hounds and thundering hooves. This auditory hallucination overwhelms the senses of her enemies, explaining the "Push" effect as they stumble back from the ghostly stampede radiating from her spinning axe.
The Inescapable Reach (Re-flavoring "Cleave")
Her ability to hit adjacent enemies represents the omnipresence of the Hunt. Just as a mortal cannot outrun Hircine’s reach, an enemy standing near Ylva finds themselves caught in the radius of her enthusiasm.
XIII. Equipment Lore: The Broken Axe
The Judge’s Gavel (Backstory for "The Butcher's Axe")
The axe lost its second blade during a duel with a cheating hedge-knight who used magical wards to repel all damage. Ylva, fueled by the conviction that he was mocking the sport, struck his enchanted shield with such force that the steel shattered. The axe broke, but the knight fell. She keeps the jagged, broken edge as a symbol that raw strength and conviction overcome those who try to rig the game.
XIV. The Endgame: The Bloodmoon Prophecy
Ylva trains for a singular, tangible goal. She watches the moon Secunda every night, waiting for it to turn crimson. She intends to participate in the Hircine’s Great Game during the Bloodmoon Prophecy. She plans to be the prey that survives, or the hunter that claims the ultimate prize. Every adventure with the party serves as preparation for this celestial olympics.



